  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_971706965" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/971706965" />
    <a title="Cecily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1199525-cecily"><img alt="Cecily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1480285828p2/1199525.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/971706965?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cecily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cecily" href="/user/show/1199525-cecily">Cecily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781857989380" href="/book/show/18378.Flowers_for_Algernon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=family-parenting">family-parenting</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=language-related">language-related</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=solitary-protagonist">solitary-protagonist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=scifi-future-speculative-fict">scifi-future-speculative-fict</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=usa-and-canada">usa-and-canada</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=relationships-twisted">relationships-twisted</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=ya">ya</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=school-location">school-location</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1199525-cecily?shelf=bildungsroman">bildungsroman</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer971706965" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16161055868698720242"><b>Who do you think you are?</b> <br/><br/>“<i>Real knowledge is to know the extent of one&apos;s ignorance.</i>” - Confucius (allegedly).<br/><br/>It’s no coincidence that <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Who_Do_You_Think_You_Are%3F_(British_TV_series)' rel='nofollow noopener'>Who do you think you are?</a> is the title of a TV genealogy series. To know oneself in the present, let alone imagine possible futures, one needs to know, remember, and understand one’s past. <br/><br/>32-year old Charlie Gordon lives alone, has an IQ of 68, and a cleaning job in a bakery. He lives in the here and now, with very few memories. Then he is selected as the first h</span>
  <span id="freeText16161055868698720242" style="display:none"><b>Who do you think you are?</b> <br><br>“<i>Real knowledge is to know the extent of one's ignorance.</i>” - Confucius (allegedly).<br><br>It’s no coincidence that <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Who_Do_You_Think_You_Are%3F_(British_TV_series)" rel="nofollow noopener">Who do you think you are?</a> is the title of a TV genealogy series. To know oneself in the present, let alone imagine possible futures, one needs to know, remember, and understand one’s past. <br><br>32-year old Charlie Gordon lives alone, has an IQ of 68, and a cleaning job in a bakery. He lives in the here and now, with very few memories. Then he is selected as the first human subject in an experiment to rapidly increase intelligence. It worked on Algernon, the mouse. <br><br>His knowledge increases exponentially, his understanding and emotional growth lag a little, and he gradually regains distressing memories of his childhood. Charlie craves intellectual information (“<i>feeding a hunger that can’t be satisfied</i>”), but is increasingly driven to discover his past, so that he can know himself, and understand his likely future. The mazes Algernon is trained and tested in become an analogy of Charlie’s life and newfound quest. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615504405i/30998779._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>Image</b>: <i>A man amid a maze</i> (<a href="https://orchestraoftheswan.org/labyrinths-funding-page/" rel="nofollow noopener">Source</a>: cover of “Labyrinths” by The Orchestra of the Swan)<br><br><br>The book covers nearly nine months (plus backstory), told by Charlie in a regular “progris riport” (later, a “Progress Report”) - an intimate diary.<br><br>The sci-fi aspect is the single surgical procedure, coupled with some enzymes. Apart from that, it’s a gripping, and sometimes heartbreaking, story that is set when and where it was written (using language of the time), but is still relevant today. <br><br><b>Ethics</b><br><br>“<i>Intelligence and education that hasn’t been tempered by human affection isn’t worth a damn.</i>”<br><br>Charlie's story demonstrates that very high intelligence is as much a special educational need, and can be as much of a personal burden, as very low. Also, that emotional intelligence and empathy are vital for happiness - both individual and societal. <br><br>You can enjoy and be moved by this novel for the story alone. However, it constantly, quietly raises ethical questions on a range of themes, without preaching, trivialising, or spoon-feeding answers. <br><br><b>Consent</b><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[A topic that's a larger part of public discourse than when the book was published.<br>What’s the intelligence threshold for informed consent for medical procedures?<br>When is it valid for one person to consent on behalf of another, especially if the intervention is experimental?<br>What about sexual encounters between people of hugely different levels of comprehension, whether that be intelligence or because at least one party is drunk?  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br><b>Difference and disability</b><br>Acceptance, adaptation, denial, and degrees of intervention and treatment form a complex knot, tugging in multiple directions. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Most parents want the best for their child, but it’s not always clear what is “best” and at what point encouragement becomes cruel pressure. <br><br>When one character said it was wrong to tamper with how God made Charlie, I recalled Lady Bracknell's opinion in <b>The Importance of Being Earnest</b> (see my review <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/24046836" rel="nofollow noopener">HERE</a>), though she meant it ironically:<br><br>“<i>I do not approve of anything that tampers with natural ignorance. Ignorance is like a delicate exotic fruit; touch it and the bloom is gone.</i>” - Oscar Wilde.<br><br>Even if you endorse a drastic intervention that might benefit an individual, the societal consequences may be different. Some deaf people are against cochlear implants, especially in children, because they reduce the richness of the deaf community, and a child can’t give informed consent on such a huge issue. And in Iceland, prenatal testing has meant almost all foetuses with Down’s Syndrome are aborted, raising fears about the status of the few who are born (see <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/down-syndrome-iceland/" rel="nofollow noopener">here</a>, for example).  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br><b>Blissful ignorance?</b><br>“<i>I wanted to know the truth, and yet I was afraid of what I might learn.</i>”<br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[We’re reminded that eating fruit from the Tree of Knowledge led to the Fall, and as Charlie comes to understand that workplace teasing and bullying was not because his co-workers thought of him as a friend, the reader sees the appeal of ignorance. Too much intelligence and knowledge creates another gulf, so it’s no easier to forge friendships than before:<br>“<i>The gap between us was widening as the current of my mind carried me swiftly into the open sea.</i>”  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615568457i/31002200._SX540_.png" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>Image</b>: <i>The ten classic Rorschach cards</i> (<a href="https://towardsdatascience.com/rorschach-tests-for-deep-learning-image-classifiers-68c019fcc9a9" rel="nofollow noopener">Source</a>)<br><br><b>Intelligence, worth, and memory</b><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[How useful are mazes and Rorschach tests for assessing intelligence, let alone value?<br>What’s the relationship with memory? Conventionally measured intelligence needs memory, but low intelligence doesn’t necessarily imply as little memory as Charlie has. And yet, as his intelligence grows, he (re)gains memories.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> <br><br><b>Sex and love</b><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Charlie's awakening includes long-supressed sexual desire, but his inexperience makes him anxious and vulnerable. Two women in the story are total opposites in how they see Charlie and thus how he feels about and behaves with them. However, I felt both were rather caricatured, and not always as believable as the other characters. That's a shame, because it's an important theme of the book, and one that may especially speak to YA readers.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br><b>Abuse with love</b><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[It seems that Charlie’s memories were suppressed because they were painful and confusing. The parent who strived to help/push/cure him was also angry and violent when he remained as he was. The other parent’s gentle acceptance of Charlie as he was led to rows. And then, when they had a normal child (actually called Norma!), things only got worse.<br>“<i>When Norma flowered, I became a weed.</i>”  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br><b>Human rights</b><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Charlie is sad when he realises a mere mouse is better at solving mazes than he is, but even back then, he thinks it’s wrong that Algernon has to pass a test to get food. He is increasingly enraged that he and Algernon are lumped together as experimental subjects - a source of pride and fame for their “creator”, Professor Nemur, who claims: <br>“<i>It might be said that Charlie Gordon did not really exist before this experiment.</i>”<br>From the start, Charlie wants to assert his independent existence as a human being, and it’s at the root of his later desire to seek out his parents:<br>“<i>If he knew I was his son, then I would be a person.</i>”  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br><b>Institutional “care”</b><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[The Warren State Home always looms, and when we see inside, it’s a believable mix of well-intentioned support in impossible circumstances, and realistic horror. Awful as it is, it’s better than some of the alternatives - for the patients as well as their families. In contrast, the Beekman College Center for Retarded Adults is objectionable only in its name. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> <br><br><b>The end</b><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[“<i>There is no way to stop the sands of knowledge from slipping through the hourglass of my mind.</i>”<br>It’s Charlie who realises the reasons for Algernon’s erratic behaviour and general decline, and that he, Charlie, will inevitably follow the same path. It must be hard to receive a dementia diagnosis after a full life: to know what’s slipping away and what the outcome will be. But to know what you’re going to lose when you’ve only just gained it, compounded by the bitter irony of having seen the previously pushy parent now with dementia, is tragic. The fact Charlie doesn’t see it that way may be because this is suitable for YA.<br><br>For most of the book, in dreams, free-association, and hallucinations, Charlie sees his younger self and refers to him in the third person: a dissociation that reflects two very different versions of himself. Sometimes, that other Charlie is so real, he seems to intervene. As he regresses, that simpler Charlie becomes more real:<br>“<i>The child in me is reclaiming my mind.</i>” <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1615568457i/31002201._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><b>Image</b>: <i>A jigsaw man piecing himself together - or maybe taking himself apart, by Stephan Schmitz</i> (<a href="https://www.theispot.com/artist/schmitz/" rel="nofollow noopener">Source</a>)<br><br><b>Publication</b><br><br>This was published as a short story in 1958 and expanded to a novel in 1966. It has won numerous awards, mainly as sci-fi. <br><br>I don’t think it’s well-known in the UK, except perhaps by sci-fi fans, but I gather it’s often read in US high schools. It’s also been challenged and banned in some instances, because Charlie struggles to understand his sexual feelings, and how to act on them appropriately. <br><br>It may be YA, but it has enough depth and breadth that is a worthwhile and moving read for adults. However, if you have a teen at home, it would be even more fruitful to read and discuss alongside them.</["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></span>
  <a data-text-id="16161055868698720242" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

